The '''black-naped fruit dove''' ('''''Ptilinopus melanospilus'''''), also known as the '''black-headed fruit dove''', is a medium-sized, up to {{cvt|24|cm}} long, green [[fruit dove]] with yellowish [[Beak|bill]] and [[Iris (anatomy)|iris]]. The male has a pale grey head with a black nape, yellow throat, and golden yellow and pink undertail [[covert]]s. The [[plumage]] of the female and the young is entirely green.

==Distribution and habitat==
The black-naped fruit dove is distributed in [[Indonesia]], [[Malaysia]] and the [[Philippines]]. In Indonesia, it is found in [[Java]], [[Lesser Sunda Islands]] and [[Sulawesi]], where it inhabits the lowland and hill [[forest]]s. The diet consists mainly of various fruits, [[Common fig|fig]]s and [[berries]]. The female usually lays one single white [[bird egg|egg]].

Widespread and common throughout its large [[range (biology)|range]], the black-naped fruit dove is evaluated as Least Concern on the [[IUCN Red List]] of Threatened Species.

